feat: enhance parallel processing system with comprehensive stress testing
- Add high concurrency stress test with 50 tasks across all priority levels - Add mixed batch and individual task execution test - Verify proper task scheduling and completion under various load scenarios - Ensure queue and worker metrics remain accurate under stress - Validate priority-based scheduling works correctly with concurrent submissions
The parallel processing system now includes: - Continuous background scheduling loop with BinaryHeap priority queue - Robust semaphore-based concurrency control - Comprehensive test coverage including stress testing - Proper cleanup and metrics tracking - Support for mixed execution patterns (batch + individual tasks)
Signed-off-by: CHEN, CHUN <jim60105@gmail.com>

feat: implement parallel processing system for batch operations
- Add TaskScheduler for managing concurrent task execution with priority queues - Implement Worker and WorkerPool for resource management and load balancing - Create Task trait and FileProcessingTask for various file operations - Add parallel processing configuration options to config system - Integrate parallel execution into match command for batch file processing - Include comprehensive test coverage for scheduler, workers, and integration scenarios - Support for CPU-intensive, IO-intensive, and mixed workload optimization
Signed-off-by: CHEN, CHUN <jim60105@gmail.com>

feat: add backlog #17 for audio processing migration to aus crate
This comprehensive backlog outlines the migration strategy from the current custom audio processing implementation (based on Symphonia) to the mature 'aus' crate ecosystem. The migration will provide:
- Enhanced spectral analysis capabilities using aus::analysis module - Improved dialogue detection with multi-feature speech activity detection - Better maintainability by leveraging proven audio processing algorithms - Performance optimizations through aus::spectrum FFT/STFT implementations
The plan includes 5 phases with detailed implementation steps, testing strategies, and compatibility measures to ensure smooth transition while maintaining API backward compatibility.
Signed-off-by: CHEN, CHUN <jim60105@gmail.com>
